body:
i was thinking of creating a compatibility layer on top of heapless to allow users to use supply `alloc::*` variants of the `heapless::*` variants if they are sure they don't care (not in embedded environment). i tried the idea a little bit but hit a hard wall with generics. `alloc::*` ones supports the `A` generic parameter (for `alloc::alloc::Allocator`) while `heapless::*` ones support `LenT`. i was able to ignore const generic `N` parameter on alloc types as rust didn't care about them when they were not used (not the case with `LenT`, sadly). so i figured this needs to be upstreamed somehow (if it suits with the views of the authors)

i wasn't able to supply `A` parameter from `core` onto `heapless`, and `LenT` parameter from `heaples`s to `core`, as i mentioned, but so far  i have something like this, using the only working generic parameter `N` , working in my wrapper module:
```
// wrapper.rs
pub mod string {
	#[cfg(feature = "alloc")]
	pub type String<const N: usize> = alloc::string::String;

	#[cfg(feature = "heapless")]
	pub type String<const N: usize> = heapless::string::String<N>;
}

pub mod vec {
	#[cfg(feature = "alloc")]
	pub type Vec<T, const N: usize> = alloc::vec::Vec<T>;

	#[cfg(feature = "heapless")]
	pub type Vec<T, const N: usize> = heapless::vec::Vec<T, N, LenT>;
}
```

which then can be used with stuff like this:
```
// some library code aiming to be general/agnostic

/// used only for embedded devices
const MAX_EXT_HEADER_LEN: usize = 256
pub enum RtspHeader<const N: usize = MAX_EXT_HEADER_LEN> {
	Accept,
	AcceptEncoding,
	...
	Extension(wrapper::string::String<N>),
}
```
and you toggle between `feature="heapless"` or ` feature="alloc"` depending on if you use this with an embedded device or not. as i said, it cannot go beyond this - no `LenT` support, and no  `A` support either, which is okay i suppose (since the user would be explicitly opting in). maybe `LenT` could be supported if this whole idea is applied directly to the heapless crate if the authors are interested. feel free to comment. i'm not sure if this is a good idea or not, or if `LenT` and/or `A` generic parameters could be solved. my idea is that maybe it might be easier to let library authors use heapless (or the wrapper) to help embedded authors utilize the libraries while letting other library users utilizing the alloc ones (using just `Vec` and `vec!` normally)

You currently cannot use from_iter directly with a &[CompactString] for example. You have to do `.into_iter().map(...)` which is annoying. I ended up building my own helper function for this but it would be nicer if the heapless crate itself provided this generic impl.

This is my helper function:

```rs
pub fn build_hstring<const N: usize, I, S>(iter: I) -> heapless::String<N>
where
    I: IntoIterator<Item = S>,
    S: AsRef<str>,
{
    let mut new = heapless::String::<N>::new();
    for c in iter {
        new.push_str(c.as_ref()).expect("build_hstring: capacity exceeded");
    }
    new
}
```
